<DOC><DOCNO> AP890621-0272 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1741EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 2ndLd-Writethru   06-21 0161</FIRST><SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0165</SECOND><HEAD>Shares Close Firmer Despite Signs of Weakness in Sterling</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: ADDS 1 graf with volume figures.</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closedfirmer on Wednesday despite further signs of weakness in sterlingand the disruption to trading caused by Britain's first nationalrail strike since 1982.   The major blue chip stocks continued their recent tendency todrift upward in spite of negative economic news, dealers said. Thepound fell sharply overnight, though it recovered somewhat later inthe day, helped by modest intervention by the Bank of England.   The Stock Exchange shortened the trading session about an hourbecause of the chaotic traffic conditions in London as a result ofthe strike.   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 7.4points, or 0.3 percent, higher at 2,172.2.   Trading volume amounted to a slender 281.4 million shares by 1500GMT, compared with 504.1 million shares traded by 1600 GMT onTuesday.</TEXT></DOC>